data-triple-N3.o: "In orthography and typography, letter case (or just case) is the distinction between the letters that are in larger upper case (capital letters, caps, majuscule, upper-case, or uppercase) and smaller lower case (minuscule, etc. ) letters in certain languages. The term originated with the shallow drawers called type cases still used to hold the movable type for letterpress printing. In the Latin script, capital letters are A, B, C, etc. ; lower case includes a, b, c, etc."@en
